"{\"uid\": \"metro.co.uk-2024-08-06-women-wear-headguards-not-men-olympic-boxing-21369308\", \"text\": \"Boxing fans will have been tuning in to catch the action at theParis2024Olympicsover the past week.  And you do not need to be eagle-eyed to have noticed that male boxers have not been wearing headguards during their rounds, while the women boxers have been donning red and blue headgear.  You'd also be forgiven for being curious about the difference, and if there is a particular health and safety reason for it.  Follow Metro.co.uk's live blog for updates from the Paris 2024 Olympics  Here's what we know.  Female boxers wear headguards at the Olympics because of rules set by the Olympic Committee (IOC) and the International Boxing Association (IBA).  Before the 2016 Olympics in Rio, both male and female athletes were made to wear headguards to improve their safety and to reduce concussions.  The decision was made after South Korean Fighter Kim Duk-Koo died after a world championship bout in 1982.  The IOC and IOA subsequently mandated that fighters at the Olympics, who are amateurs, must wear head protection for their own safety.  However, this changed in 2016 when a study from the Global Sport Institute revealed that boxers fighting with no head gear were less likely to suffer concussions.  This allowed men to fight without headgear, but given the study was only conducted on males, the IOC decided that women should continue to wear headgear out of an abundance of caution.  In 2013, theWall Street Journalwrote that then-chairman of the AIBA medical commission, Dr Charles Butler, explained that concussion was less of an issue with women fighters due to their strength.  However, in 2021,Naturereported that women sports players are at greater risk of traumatic brain injuries, and often 'fare worse' after a concussion, than their male counterparts.  Following the rule change, an observationalstudy published in 2017concurred that 'the number of stoppages due to head blows was significantly decreased without headguards' in male boxing.  All minors (boys and girls), schoolchildren, juniors, youth and Senior Elite and Senior Development Females must also fight with headwear.  Follow Metro across our social channels, onFacebook,TwitterandInstagram  Share your views in the comments below  ArrowMORE:Adam Peaty reveals grim Olympic Village catering; says 'worms' are found in food  ArrowMORE:Swimmer kicked out of Olympic Village hits back at claims of 'inappropriate' behaviour  ArrowMORE:Paula Radcliffe speaks out on Olympic disqualification controversy - before stunning U-turn  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy\"}"